summary:
I am a senior lecturer at Leiden University, where I teach "the history of psychology", as well as some classes on the cognitive neuroscience of decision making.

Ever since obtainint my PhD in 2014, I have devoted my career to teaching various topics in cognitive neuroscience and psychology. I developed and taught the courses "brain mechanisms of decision making" and "developmental cognitive neuroscience". In addition, I supervised students' research internships, as well as assisting in the teaching and supervision of several other courses, such as programming, academic writing, and neuroanatomy.

I obtained my PhD in 2014. For my PhD research, I studied the neural substrate of speeded decision making.

Specialties: Teaching, Academic presenting, functional Magnetic Resonance Imaging (fMRI). the basal ganglia, decision making. developmental cognitive neuroscience
